    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName ref="pl0076">Edinburgh</placeName> Sept 14<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1769</dateline>
                <opener>
                    <salute>My Lord</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>Permit me to return my humble thanks for the honor you did me at <placeName ref="pl0110">Athol house</placeName>: &amp; I beg leave to assure your Grace
                    I should be extremely happy of an opportunity of shewing my gratitude in any
                    shape. If my Lord you are forming a collection of minerals, I may possibly add a
                    few from my own Country that are not common.</p>
                <p>I have considered what your Grace mentioned in respect to the engraving reduced
                    plates of <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0017">the great
                        Zoology</title>
                    </bibl>. I allow that a portable Zoology is much to be
                    desired; but fear the censure of the world for publishing a lesser edition after
                    putting it to the expence of a larger.<note type="editorial">Despite these
                        misgivings, Pennant did produce a 'portable' octavo edition of his <bibl type="authorial">
                            <title ref="bi0018">
                                <hi rend="italic">British
                                    Zoology</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl>, the title page of which gives a
                        publication date of 1768. Pennant may be referring in this letter to the
                        notion of publishing a more compact volume that would reproduce the full set
                        of <persName ref="pe0576">Peter Paillou's</persName> 107 plates from the
                        1766 edition of <bibl type="editorial">
                            <title ref="bi0017">
                                <hi rend="italic">The British Zoology</hi>
                            </title>
                        </bibl>. No such project was
                        ever undertaken.</note> all I can propose is that I w<hi rend="superscript">d</hi> join with any Gentleman for <rs type="art" ref="ar0093">engraving
                        some of the most capital birds of the great plates</rs>; not for sale but to
                    give away to friends. not but it would be prudent to take the more lucrative
                    method, for the Germans are now <bibl type="authorial">
                        <title ref="bi0234">copying &amp; translating the great
                            work</title>
                    </bibl>. but as I dedicated that to a charity, I must do
                    nothing that may carry reflections with it.</p>
                <p>If your Grace honors me with the drawing of the Lizard please to inclose it to me
                    at <placeName ref="pl0001">Downing Flintshire</placeName>.</p>
                <p>I take the Liberty of presenting my best respects to <persName ref="pe0577">the
                        Dutchess</persName> &amp; <persName ref="pe0578">Captain
                    Murray</persName>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>&amp; am my Lord <lb/>Your Grace's <lb/>most obliged <lb/>&amp;
                            obed<hi rend="superscript">t</hi> humble Serv<hi rend="superscript">t</hi>
                    </salute>
                    <signed>
                        <persName ref="pe0232">Tho.
                        Pennant</persName>
                    </signed>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="pl0076">Edinburgh</placeName> Sept<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> 15<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>
                        1769.</dateline>
                </closer>
